Sample Description: Pale green to white, coarse-grained, epidote-chlorite-actinolite-bearing felsic schist. It contains quartz and plagioclase crystals whose abundance and concentration suggest that the protolith was a plagioclase and quartz-eye bearing porphyry. Its chemical composition is consistent with an andesite protolith. Gradation between fine- and coarse-grained layers is typical. A penetrative stretching lineation is defined by rods and extended aggregates of grey-blue quartz and chalky white plagioclase.
Lab: University of Alberta
Primary Reference: Canadian Journal of Earth Sciences, Canadian Science Publishing, v.42/p.1449-1465

Sample Description: Medium grained, potassic altered, Phase 1 diorite. The porphyry contains 35% sercitized anorthitic plagioclase (0.5-2mm in diameter), 7% potassium feldspar (1-5mm in diameter) with inclusions of hornblende in an altered, fine-grained groundmass. Overprinted by pervasive and vein-controlled secondary potassium feldspar, quartz, biotite, chlorite, magnetite, pyrite and chalcopyrite.
Lab:
University of British Columbia
for Isotopic and Geochemical Research (UBC)
Authors: Febbo, G.E., Kennedy, L.A., Savell, M., Creaser, R.A., and Friedman, R.M.

Sample Description: Medium grained, chlorite and phyllic altered, Phase 1 diorite that outcrops adjacent to the high quartz zone. The porphyry contains 35% sercitized laths interpreted to be replaced plagioclase (1-2mm in diameter), 8% chlorite rhombohedral aggregates interpreted to be replaced hornblende (0.5-1mm in diameter) and 5% equant anhedral potassium feldspar partially replaced to sericite (2-3mm diameter) in an altered, fine-grained groundmass. The intrusion is overprinted by Stage 2 sericite-chlorite-pyrite alteration with disseminations of secondary magnetite, trace chalcopyrite, 2% pyrite and ~10% quartz-chalcopyrite-pyrite veins by volume.
Lab:
University of British Columbia
for Isotopic and Geochemical Research (UBC)
Authors: Febbo, G.E., Kennedy, L.A., Savell, M., Creaser, R.A., and Friedman, R.M.

Sample Description: Fine grained Phase 2 diorite plug that cuts the high quartz zone and is overprinted by Stage 2 phyllic alteration. The porphyry contains 30% sericitized laths (~1mm long) interpreted to be replaced by plagioclase, 5% chlorite aggregates interpreted to be replaced by hornblende, and 5% anhedral inclusion-rich K-feldspar in a fine-grained groundmass. The intrusion is overprinted by Stage 2 sericite-chlorite-pyrite alteration with 1% secondary magnetite, trace chalcopyrite and stringers of anhydrite and calcite.
Lab:
University of British Columbia
for Isotopic and Geochemical Research (UBC)
Authors: Febbo, G.E., Kennedy, L.A., Savell, M., Creaser, R.A., and Friedman, R.M.

Sample Description: Stage 2 quartz-pyrite vein with yellow sericite alteration haloes in intensely sericite-pyrite-chlorite altered andesite breccia. The vein host rock contains juvenile porphyritic angular andesite fragments 60% clasts 1cm in diameter with < 1% subrounded granule-sized felsic clasts. The host rock is intensely altered to sericite-pyrite-chlorite and is well foliated. The molybdenite-bearing vein is 3-4mm wide with wavy margins, is parallel to foliation and contains a thin (1mm) selvage of white and yellow sericite alteration. The vein contains 75% grey-white microcrystalline quartz, 15% blue-grey elongate molybdenite disseminations, 8% brass-yellow anhedral to subhedral pyrite disseminations (<0.2; mm) and 2% sericite.
Lab: University of Alberta
Authors: Febbo, G.E., Kennedy, L.A., Savell, M., Creaser, R.A., and Friedman, R.M.
